Troubleshooting Tips
Service won't start:

Check if port 8000 is already in use: sudo lsof -i :8000
Kill existing process: sudo kill -9 <PID>
Verify virtual environment is activated
Import errors:

Ensure all dependencies installed: pip list | grep -E "fastapi|uvicorn|pydantic|psutil"
Reinstall if needed: pip install --upgrade fastapi uvicorn pydantic psutil
Policy checks always fail:

Verify PolicyCheckRequest model matches the JSON structure
Check that policy functions return tuples: (bool, str)
Print debug information in policy functions
System status shows errors:

Ensure psutil is installed correctly
Test psutil directly: python3 -c "import psutil; print(psutil.cpu_percent())"
Conclusion
You've successfully built a FastAPI service that:

Monitors system resources (CPU, memory, disk)
Exposes status information via REST endpoints
Enforces configurable policies on requests
Validates request size, HTTP methods, and rate limits
Implements middleware for request logging
This type of service is essential in DevOps environments for:

Health Monitoring: Tracking service and system health
Policy Enforcement: Ensuring requests meet organizational standards
Rate Limiting: Protecting services from abuse
Observability: Logging and monitoring API usage
These patterns are used in production systems for API gateways, service meshes, and microservice architectures. You can extend this lab by adding authentication, database storage for rate limiting, or integration with monitoring tools like Prometheus.
